Less in point of number, but highly consequential to the tranquillity of the whole province, have been the four cities of the Abi- pones, the two of Mocobios, one of TobaS, and another of MbayaS, warlike and equestriau na- tions. To these add the pedestrian nations, the Lules, VileIas, Chiriguanos, Chunipies, Ho- moampaS, &c. converted by us to the Roman rites and discipline in their own colonies. In language, manners, and religious observanceS, they differ amongst themselves3 they are all, however, attached to agriculture.

Very many Indian towns have long since ceased to exist, sometimes from the inconstancy of the Indians sighing for their native land, sometimes from the malevolence, the avarice, or inertness of the Europeans.
